text: 3.1 Day-to-Day Management
label: HH1

text: Mutually acceptable, formal procedural, reporting and communication processes and structures
label: BODY

text: will be established in order to manage the delivery of the Services in an efficient and effective
label: BODY

text: manner. Such processes and structures will be documented and maintained by Vendor as part
label: BODY

text: of the Procedures Manual, as approved by VITA, and modified and updated on an ongoing
label: BODY

text: basis to reflect changes to the business and operational relationship.
label: BODY

text: Vendor and VITA will agree upon additional points of contact and a reporting structure covering
label: BODY

text: day-to-day operations and reviews of Vendor’s performance. These may include technical,
label: BODY

text: financial, and Service Level reviews as well as the resolution of any other issues that may arise.
label: BODY

text: These reporting schedules will be documented and maintained by Vendor as part of the
label: BODY

text: Procedures Manual and in an online repository accessible to VITA’s management team.  A
label: BODY

text: regular meeting schedule will be required for the different reporting levels established, with
label: BODY

text: ongoing 24-hour access to all of VITA’s Vendor points of contact when required. Vendor must
label: BODY

text: provide processes and procedures acceptable to VITA and consistent with the terms of the
label: BODY

text: Agreement that can be used to manage the day-to-day relationship process and shall at
label: BODY

text: minimum include:
label: BODY

text: a. Change Control Management Procedures (for example, system technical
label: BODY

text: changes);
label: BODY

text: b. Dispute Resolution Process;
label: BODY

text: c. Contract/Pricing Administration Management and Change Procedures;
label: BODY

text: d. System Monitoring and Event Reporting Procedures;
label: BODY

text: e. Service-Level and Performance Reporting Procedures;
label: BODY

text: Service Requests and Work Orders Procedures;
label: BODY

text: g. Reporting mechanism with up-to-date status of all ongoing projects and
label: BODY

text: outstanding Service Requests;
label: BODY

text: h. System Workload Performance and Trending Analysis Procedures;
label: BODY

text: Problem Escalation Procedures;
label: BODY

text: Security Management and Reporting Procedures;
label: BODY

text: k. IT Service Continuity and Disaster Recovery Planning Procedures;
label: BODY

text: Emergency Management Procedures; and
label: BODY

text: m. Commonwealth Policy and Procedures.
label: BODY

text: Both Parties shall establish relationship management teams to perform the primary business
label: BODY

text: management support functions that include, at a minimum, the roles and responsibilities that
label: BODY

text: follow.

text: 3.1.1 Executive Management
label: HH1

text: Relationship Executive is the senior member of a Party’s Relationship Management leadership
label: BODY

text: team who has high level oversight of the Agreement and relationship to provide direction and
label: BODY

text: enable implementation of the strategic vision of the Commonwealth through development of the
label: BODY

text: appropriate portfolio of IT Services and related competencies and skills and enable the
label: BODY

text: management of strategic relationships and partnerships.  The Relationship Executive shall:
label: BODY

text: a. Have significant organizational influence in his or her respective entity to
label: BODY

text: adequately bring any needed priority, resources, or decision-making authority
label: BODY

text: necessary to ensure the correct level of support to the relationship;
label: BODY

text: b. Develop and articulate a Service delivery strategy that supports the
label: BODY

text: Commonwealth’s business strategies;
label: BODY

text: c. Select and approve the business case(s) for recommended IT Service delivery
label: BODY

text: initiatives;
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: services delivery relationships; and
label: BODY

text: Act as the executive-level liaison with strategic business partners and customers.
label: BODY

text: 3.1.2 Relationship Management
label: HH1

text: The Relationship Manager (“RM”) is the primary interface between the Parties. The RM shall:
label: BODY

text: a. Be responsible for contract management, financial management and quality
label: BODY

text: assurance;
label: BODY

text: b. Coordinate communications between the Parties;
label: BODY

text: c. Set directions and priorities of the respective Party;
label: BODY

text: d. Monitor the contract;
label: BODY

text: e. Manage day-to-day interactions based on the identified requirements;
label: BODY

text: Ensure understanding of and agreement to Service Levels;
label: BODY

text: g. Implement required changes to Services and Service Levels;
label: BODY

text: h. With respect to the Commonwealth, through the Performance Management
label: BODY

text: function, review and monitor Vendor performance against Service Levels, project
label: BODY

text: plans and performance improvement plans;
label: BODY

text: Monitor and amend Agreement, including the reviewing of proposed contract
label: BODY

text: amendments;
label: BODY

text: Resolve Incidents and Problems;
label: BODY

text: k. Oversee the implementation of financial policies and procedures related to the
label: BODY

text: Services;
label: BODY

text: Coordinate the operational governance processes between the Commonwealth
label: BODY

text: and Vendor;
label: BODY

text: m. Be responsible for building effective relationships between the Parties; and
label: BODY

text: n. Keep other Party informed and identify and communicate opportunities to leverage
label: BODY

text: the Services more effectively.
label: BODY
